cs.SI, cs.GT, cs.SOC, cs.MA, cs.CE. 

The paper discusses a stochastic network disease game model that captures the self-interests of individuals during the spread of a susceptible-infected-susceptible (SIS) disease where individuals react to current risk of disease spread, and their reactions together with the current state of the disease stochastically determine the next stage of the disease. The paper uses game theory to consider how individuals make rational decisions by reasoning strategically about the decisions of others. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). The paper also discusses the effects of individual preemptive measures on infectious disease spread over networks, which falls under cs.SOC (Computational Social Science). Additionally, the paper proposes a stochastic model, which involves probability and randomness, and thus falls under cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) and cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science).
